Anonymous Mon 30 May 2022 21:22:52 No.48137745 Report
Quoted By: >>48137912 >>48138314 >>48141626
>>48136496
>the truth is that "years of drawing" doesn't mean much: it's either years of casually drawing the goofy shit you want to draw or years of actual practice and study that makes the difference.
From what I've seen from both my own nearly non-existent practice and the progress of others over the years, it's kind of in the middle. Super serious artists indeed spend weeks focusing on studies, and they indeed improve your skill. But just drawing shit you want to draw with an eye for improving yourself will actually make you a better artist. It's just developing technique and a "feel". Snobs will look down upon it, or (correctly) point out all the flaws that remain because you're not focusing your practice, but you will improve.

It's just that the will has to be there. To look at your own stuff and see mistakes, and to erase "progress" because you spotted a mistake. Or even to just throw yourself at a task until you get it right. And doing it again next time. Even if you never become good according to your own or others' metrics, you will definitely improve.
